In this statement, President Obama reflects on the observance of Juneteenth, which commemorates the delayed but welcome news of freedom for the slaves of Galveston, Texas. He acknowledges the slow progress towards equality and justice for African-Americans in the United States, and compares it to the ongoing struggles for freedom and justice faced by marginalized groups today. The President calls for a recommitment to the work that remains undone, including efforts to combat modern-day slavery and honor those who fought for a more just society.